1)

	Firstly I had would have to work out the diameter of a penny. This could be done either via the internet or by drawing a circle round the penny then measuring it from side to side.
The diameter of the penny is 19mm.

	Next the total floor space of the golden gate bridge would have to be considered. Using Wikipedia, the width of the bridge is 27.4 meters while the length is 2,737.4 meters.
This gives a total area of 75004.76 m2.

	So that the coins don’t overlap we will in fact presume they are squares so that only the edges of the coins will touch. The square will have sides of 19mm(or 0.019m). Therefore the area a singular coin will cover will be 0.000361 m2.

	Next using a calculator, I have divided the total area of the bridge by the area of a singular penny. This will give the total number of pennies that could fit on the bridge.
Total number of pennies that could fit on the bridge: 207769418, with a little space left over.


